The developed model was cross validated by the LOO method [36]. The q
2 value is <0.5 (Eq. 2), which showed that the developed model is invalid. According to the recommendations of Kim et al. [37], however, regression models are acceptable if the value of the standard deviation (SD, Table 1) is <0.3. Because the value of standard deviation is <0.3, the developed model (Eq. 2) is a valid one. Furthermore, the observed and predicted antibacterial activity values are close to each other (Table 12), so the mt-QSAR model for antibacterial activity (Eq. 2) is a valid one. The plot of predicted pMIC
ab against observed pMIC
ab (Fig. 1) also favours the developed model expressed by Eq. (2). Further, the plot of observed pMIC
ab versus residual pMIC
ab (Fig. 2) indicated that there was no systemic error in model development because the propagation of error was observed on both sides of zero [38].




Kier’s second-order shape index (κ
2) was found to be the most dominating descriptor explaining the antifungal activity of the synthesized substituted hydrazide derivatives (Table 11).

